// compiler/codegen/nvptx_p8_vec_add_scale_test.hexa
// RFC 071 P8 — source-to-silicon vec_add scale-up test fixture
//
// @version 0.0.1
// @capabilities [pure]
// @phase("parse_only")
//
// Scale-up follow-on to N35 (`c29359ab`) which proved source-to-silicon
// E2E PASS at N=1024 (single block · 1024 threads · exactly one CTA).
// This fixture is THE SAME kernel shape (vec-add with bounds check), so
// the codegen-correctness work is *not* repeated here — the test is
// purely a launch-side scale-up: does the kernel scale to large N when
// the host launcher provides a multi-block grid?
//
// The bounds check `to_i64(gid) < n` is what enables grid scaling: when
// gridX > 1, every thread computes `gid = ctaid.x * ntid.x + tid.x` and
// only the threads with `gid < n` write to c[]. For N a multiple of
// blockX=1024, no threads are masked off; for non-multiples, the tail
// threads silently no-op.
//
// Kernel name = `vec_add` (distinct from N34's `my_test_kernel` and from
// N50's `vec_mul`) so the falsifier can substring-assert
// `.visible .entry vec_add` and rule out fixture-cross-contamination.
//
// Host launcher (host_vec_add_scale.c) sweeps 6 shapes:
//   N ∈ {1024, 16384, 262144, 1048576, 4194304, 16777216}
//        (1K,   16K,   256K,   1M,      4M,      16M)
// With blockX=1024, gridX = (N + 1023) / 1024 = N/1024 for these powers.
//
// F-RFC071-E2E-VEC-ADD-SCALE-NUMERIC-EQ: all 6 shapes byte-equal vs CPU
//   reference (FP64 add is bit-exact per IEEE 754, mul.f64 is not
//   relevant here, no FMA contraction possible for a single add).
// F-RFC071-E2E-VEC-ADD-SCALE-BANDWIDTH: at N ≥ 1M (bandwidth-saturated
//   regime), measured GB/s should approach RTX 5070 theoretical
//   (~672 GB/s LPDDR5X). >50% of theoretical = >336 GB/s expected.

// ── The kernel (gpu/SPEC.md §2 — @gpu_kernel must return void) ───────

@gpu_kernel
fn vec_add(a: [f64], b: [f64], c: [f64], n: i64) {
    let gid = gpu_block_id_x() * gpu_block_dim_x() + gpu_thread_id_x()
    if to_i64(gid) < n {
        c[to_i64(gid)] = a[to_i64(gid)] + b[to_i64(gid)]
    }
}
